def load_and_merge_wids_data(functional_path, quantitative_path, categorical_path, targets_path=None):
    import pandas as pd

    # Load files
    functional_df = pd.read_csv(functional_path)
    quantitative_df = pd.read_excel(quantitative_path)
    categorical_df = pd.read_excel(categorical_path)

    # Merge metadata
    metadata = pd.merge(quantitative_df, categorical_df, on="participant_id", how="inner")
    merged_df = pd.merge(functional_df, metadata, on="participant_id", how="inner")

    # Merge targets if available
    if targets_path:
        targets_df = pd.read_excel(targets_path)
        merged_df = pd.merge(merged_df, targets_df, on="participant_id", how="inner")

    return merged_df

1. Load Dataset and Basic Preprocessing¶

Step 1–4: Load and Preprocess Data We begin by loading the final merged training dataset and checking its structure. Then, we engineer two new features: age group buckets and a sex–age interaction term. Next, categorical variables like ethnicity, race, and scan location are one-hot encoded. Finally, we prepare our feature matrix X by dropping IDs and target columns, and separately store the targets y_adhd and y_sex for classification.

In [1]:

7.Feature Selection for ADHD Prediction by Sex¶

We use a Random Forest classifier to compute feature importances separately for male and female participants. Top 20 features per group are selected based on importance scores. Missing values are imputed using median values before training.

In [8]:
def run_feature_selection_sex_split(data, label_col="ADHD_Outcome_x", top_k=20):
    X = data.drop(columns=["participant_id", "Sex", "ADHD_Outcome_x", "ADHD_Outcome_y"], errors='ignore')
    y = data[label_col]

    imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy="median")
    X_imputed = pd.DataFrame(imputer.fit_transform(X), columns=X.columns)

    rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
    rf.fit(X_imputed, y)
    importances = pd.Series(rf.feature_importances_, index=X.columns)
    return importances.sort_values(ascending=False).head(top_k)

# Run feature selection
top_male_adhd = run_feature_selection_sex_split(male_df)
top_male_adhd.to_csv("top_features_adhd_male.csv")

top_female_adhd = run_feature_selection_sex_split(female_df)
top_female_adhd.to_csv("top_features_adhd_female.csv")

def run_feature_selection_general(df, target="Sex", top_k=20):
    X = df.drop(columns=["participant_id", "Sex", "ADHD_Outcome_x", "ADHD_Outcome_y"], errors='ignore')
    y = df[target]

    imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy="median")
    X_imputed = pd.DataFrame(imputer.fit_transform(X), columns=X.columns)

    rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
    rf.fit(X_imputed, y)
    importances = pd.Series(rf.feature_importances_, index=X.columns)
    return importances.sort_values(ascending=False).head(top_k)

# Get top features for predicting sex
top_sex = run_feature_selection_general(df)
top_sex.to_csv("top_features_sex.csv")

def plot_top_features(df, label_col, title, output_file, color):
    X = df.drop(columns=["participant_id", label_col])
    y = df[label_col]
    
    model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
    model.fit(X, y)

    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
    plt.xlabel("Feature Importance Score")
    plt.ylabel("Feature")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.tight_layout()
